e concepts of dependency, responsibility and rights and their significance for social citizenship; draws together findings from a range of recent research that has investigated popular, political, welfare provider and welfare user discourses; discusses, in a UK context, the relevance of the recent Human Rights Act for social policy; presents arguments in favour of a human rights based approach to social welfare. The book is essential reading for anyone concerned about the future of welfare. It is aimed at students and academics in social policy, social work, sociology, politics and law. It will also interest policy makers and welfare professionals, particularly those concerned with welfare benefits and social care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic welfarexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPublic welfarezGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aDean, Hartley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDean, Hartley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoheny, Shane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllis, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrton, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRogers, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z97831111962130 cprintz978186134562240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847425881423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847425881/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2